      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/glen_aubrey_new_york"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "The hamlet flourished around flour, lumber, and tanning, with a tannery opening in the 1850s that employed many locals.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        15,
        28,
        30
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/glen_aubrey_new_york"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "New York State Route 26 cuts through Glen Aubrey, linking it 12 miles south to Endicott and 6 miles north to I‑81 at Whitney Point.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        11
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glen_Aubrey%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "Glen Aubrey sits in the valley of the East Branch of Nanticoke Creek, which flows south to the Susquehanna River.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        12
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glen_Aubrey%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "From 1950 to 1962 a brief stock car raceway drew regional crowds before the site became a mobile home park.",
